title: Starting order for Can-Am Duel race No. 1 at Daytona
text:
Feb 19, 2017 at 6:33p ET 0Shares 
Chase Elliott will start on the pole for the 59th running of the Daytona 500 and leads off the first Can-Am Duel race on Thursday night at 7 p.m. on FS1. 
The two Duel races will help to decide positions 3-40 and which two cars won't make the field. 
Check out the starting lineup for the first Can-Am Duel. John Harrelson / LAT Photo USA 1 Chase Elliott 
Chase Elliott became the fifth driver in NASCAR history to win back-to-back Daytona 500 poles. The 21-year-old driver looks to survive the Can-Am Duel on Thursday night and then have a better performance this year in the Daytona 500. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 2 Brad Keselowski 
Team Penske was the fastest in practice on Saturday afternoon but the Fords dropped off a bit in qualifying. Keselowski posted the top time until the two Hendrick cars knocked him off in the final session. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 3 Martin Truex Jr. 
After struggles to get through the pre-race inspection, Truex posted the fifth fastest time in qualifying. The Toyotas had a ton of speed in the Clash, we’ll see how that transfers through the rest of Speedweeks. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk Michael L. Levitt 4 Kevin Harvick 
The move to Ford doesn’t seem to be setting Stewart-Haas Racing back too far as both Kevin Harvick and Clint Bowyer had a ton of speed in qualifying. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 5 Matt Kenseth 
Kenseth has won the Duel twice in his NASCAR career and looks to be one of the fastest cars heading into the 150-mile Duel races. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 6 Kyle Busch 
Kyle Busch has won a Duel race four times in his NASCAR career, including one last year that started him on the second row. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 7 Ricky Stenhouse Jr. 
Roush Fenway Racing showed a lot of speed in practice and came close to the top 10 in qualifying. Stenhouse was the first car on the outside looking in for the second qualifying session. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 8 Daniel Suarez 
The rookie learned a lot in his first weekend in a Cup Series car. He put together a strong showing in the Clash and qualified in 15 th . A strong finish in the Can-Am Duel will only help his confidence for the 500. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 9 Joey Logano 
Joey Logano appeared to be the victim of a change in the wind direction as he was one of several fast practice cars who underperformed in qualifying. With a win in the Clash under his belt, Logano proved he knows how to win shootouts at Daytona. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 10 Trevor Bayne 
Like his Roush Fenway Racing teammate, Bayne was fast in practice but didn’t live up to the hype in qualifying. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 11 Paul Menard 
Paul Menard didn’t come out with a very strong performance in qualifying for the No. 27 Richard Childress Racing Chevrolet. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 12 Jamie McMurray 
From what McMurray showed in the Clash, he’ll look to run better in a crowd of cars over a single-car run. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 13 Aric Almirola 
Almirola showed a ton of speed in practice but fell off similarly to Joey Logano and Ryan Blaney. The conditions seemed to knock off some of the No. 43’s speed. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 14 Landon Cassill 
Cassill makes the flip from the No. 38 to No. 34 for Front Row Motorsports and will have some work to do in the Can-Am Duel. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 15 Matt DiBenedetto 
A new ride for DiBenedetto didn’t see much higher results. He’ll start near the back of the first Duel race. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 16 Chris Buescher 
Buescher was the slower of the JTG Daugherty Racing tandem. He’ll have to make a lot of passes if he wants to start near the front of the Great American Race. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 17 Brendan Gaughan 
The veteran XFINITY Series driver locked his No. 75 into the field as one of six drivers that have to make the field on time. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk John K Harrelson 18 Michael Waltrip 
The two-time Daytona 500 winner makes his final appearance behind the wheel in his 30 th running of the Great American Race. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 19 Reed Sorenson 
Reed Sorenson has to race against three other drivers for the final two open spots in the starting lineup. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk John K Harrelson 20 Joey Gase 
A slow start to the weekend for the BK Racing team has Joey Gase starting in the back of the first Duel race. Jasen Vinlove Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports 21 Timmy Hill 
One of four drivers who has to battle for two spots, Timmy Hill has to beat out Reed Sorenson to improve his odds of making the Daytona 500 field. , LAT Images www.latphoto.co.uk Michael L. Levitt
